1
00:00:11,897 --> 00:00:13,209
What are you doing?

2
00:00:13,211 --> 00:00:16,012
Pigeon check for Sheldon.

3
00:00:16,013 --> 00:00:18,047
North side's all clear!

4
00:00:18,048 --> 00:00:20,349
Great. Let's look
at some planets!

5
00:00:20,352 --> 00:00:23,352
Hey, why'd you lug your
telescope all the way over here?

6
00:00:23,354 --> 00:00:24,988
Leonard has one
in our apartment.

7
00:00:24,990 --> 00:00:26,723
Yeah, I'm gonna
use Leonard's.

8
00:00:26,724 --> 00:00:30,259
Might as well hold my hand
up like this and squint.

9
00:00:30,261 --> 00:00:32,796
I don't know.
It seemed pretty good.

10
00:00:32,797 --> 00:00:34,764
You know, once
when the cable went out,

11
00:00:34,765 --> 00:00:36,566
I watched an entire episode
of The Bachelor

12
00:00:36,567 --> 00:00:39,401
on a TV across the street.

13
00:00:39,404 --> 00:00:41,638
This one's more
of a professional model.

14
00:00:41,639 --> 00:00:43,273
So was the girl he picked!

15
00:00:43,274 --> 00:00:48,077
This baby's got a ten-inch
diameter with f/10 ACF optics.

16
00:00:48,078 --> 00:00:49,511
And tonight

17
00:00:49,514 --> 00:00:52,414
Mercury is
at its highest elongation.

18
00:00:52,416 --> 00:00:57,986
It makes far-away things seem
close, and Mercury is a planet.

19
00:00:57,989 --> 00:01:00,856
I know Mercury is a planet.

20
00:01:00,858 --> 00:01:03,258
But the-the other
thing was helpful.

21
00:01:03,261 --> 00:01:05,661
Oh. Look at that.

22
00:01:05,663 --> 00:01:08,264
- Neil Gaiman tweeted about my store!
- What did he say?

23
00:01:08,266 --> 00:01:09,898
Uh, "Next time
you're in Pasadena,

24
00:01:09,901 --> 00:01:11,467
"check out The Comic Center.

25
00:01:11,470 --> 00:01:13,268
"Great vibe,
old school,

26
00:01:13,271 --> 00:01:15,304
the owner really knows
his stuff."

27
00:01:15,307 --> 00:01:17,172
Isn't that amazing?

28
00:01:17,175 --> 00:01:19,441
Well, uh, it's no Sandman,
but I guess we can't expect

29
00:01:19,444 --> 00:01:21,977
everything he writes
to be a masterpiece.

30
00:01:21,979 --> 00:01:23,580
When was he in your store?

31
00:01:23,581 --> 00:01:26,449
I have no idea.
I think I would remember that.

32
00:01:26,450 --> 00:01:29,886
Obviously, vibranium is the
most powerful metal in comics.

33
00:01:29,887 --> 00:01:31,920
What, more powerful
than adamantium?

34
00:01:31,922 --> 00:01:33,523
He's right.

35
00:01:33,524 --> 00:01:36,125
Wolverine's claws,
Ultron's outer shell.

36
00:01:36,127 --> 00:01:37,593
Need I go on?

37
00:01:37,595 --> 00:01:40,129
You don't need to,
but you probably will.

38
00:01:41,333 --> 00:01:44,099
What about Wonder
Woman's bracelets?

39
00:01:44,101 --> 00:01:45,401
Good point.

40
00:01:45,402 --> 00:01:49,105
Strong as a metal and
fierce as a fashion choice.

41
00:01:49,106 --> 00:01:50,440
You know,

42
00:01:50,441 --> 00:01:51,874
Thor's hammer's
pretty powerful,

43
00:01:51,877 --> 00:01:54,711
and in the comics,
it's made out of enchanted uru.

44
00:01:54,712 --> 00:01:56,946
Uh, yeah, I think
it's the enchantment

45
00:01:56,947 --> 00:01:58,947
that's powerful,
not the uru,

46
00:01:58,950 --> 00:02:01,985
but, uh, thanks for playing.

47
00:02:03,788 --> 00:02:06,154
Oh, man, I can't believe
Neil Gaiman came in,

48
00:02:06,157 --> 00:02:07,230
and we weren't even there.

49
00:02:07,230 --> 00:02:10,230
